WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.000
6.0 English

2
00:00:03.000 --> 00:00:06.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hello, this is 6 Minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.000
I'm Neil.

5
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Beth.

6
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Many of those leading the fight against climate change are young people who feel betrayed by politicians and adults.

7
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:29.000
In survey after survey, children report feeling that they have no future, that humanity is doomed and that governments are failing to act.

8
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.000
This is causing many young people to feel worried about the state of the planet. There's even a name for it.

9
00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Climate anxiety.

10
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:43.000
And it's also creating conflict between adults and children in families and schools.

11
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:50.000
What's certain is that a solution to the climate emergency needs the corporation of everyone, both old and young.

12
00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:56.000
So can talking honestly about the climate help mend the divisions between generations.

13
00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
That's what we'll be discussing in this program along with some useful new vocabulary.

14
00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:04.000
But first I have a question for you, Neil.

15
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:11.000
Many young people's hopes and fears about climate change are symbolized by the Swedish activist Greta Tumberg.

16
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:22.000
These days, Greta travels the world, speaking about the climate emergency, but her protests started much smaller in her hometown Stockholm.

17
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
So how did Greta Tumberg's climate activism begin?

18
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Did she, A, plant trees in her school garden?

19
00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:37.000
B, skip school on Fridays, or C, recycle her school's plastic waste?

20
00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Hmm, I think Greta Tumberg went on strike and skipped school on Fridays.

21
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.000
Okay, Neil, I will reveal the correct answer later in the program.

22
00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:54.000
One recent survey showed that three quarters or more of young people in the UK feel the future is frightening.

23
00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:02.000
Here, ME aged 14 and Milly 11 share some of our fears with BBC ideas.

24
00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:12.000
If climate change were like an animal or a plant, I think it'd be some sort of parasite, because it's the only thing that's actually growing and getting bigger,

25
00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.000
while everything else starts dying off.

26
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:24.000
I think climate change is like really scary and the fact that lots of people aren't doing much about it just sort of freaks me out.

27
00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:29.000
The environment is definitely very special, because if we get rid of it, there's no or else we can go.

28
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:33.000
Like, it's a very one-in-a-million-suit of planet.

29
00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:36.000
ME calls climate change a parasite.

30
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:43.000
In the natural world, a parasite is an animal or plant that lives on another living thing and feeds from it.

31
00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:51.000
If you describe a person as a parasite, you mean they are lazy and live off other people supporting them or giving them money.

32
00:02:51.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Likewise, ME thinks climate change is sucking the goodness out of the planet, and she uses a swang idiom to describe her feelings.

33
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:08.000
It freaks me out. If something freaks you out, it makes you become very emotional, upset, or confused.

34
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:14.000
MELEE agrees, what freaks her out is that governments don't seem to be doing much about the problem.

35
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:20.000
It's not as if we can escape anywhere. Human kind only has one home, planet Earth.

36
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:25.000
MELEE calls Earth one in a million, meaning very special or rare.

37
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:27.000
So what can be done?

38
00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Psychotherapist Caroline Hickman has visited 10 countries around the world, talking to over a hundred thousand teenagers about their climate fears.

39
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:42.000
They told her about parents ignoring them when they wanted to discuss their feelings, and adults telling them,

40
00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:45.000
fixing the planet is your job now.

41
00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:50.000
Here she gives BBC ideas some advice on discussing climate change with children.

42
00:03:51.000 --> 00:04:02.000
My advice to adults parents teaches is, do not put it off, don't push it away, don't save it up, and just have that big conversation.

43
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Talk about it regularly, that's crucial.

44
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:10.000
And it's okay for you to say to your children, I don't have all the answers.

45
00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.000
We're not sure exactly how to deal with all of this, but let's find out together.

46
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:24.000
Caroline's top tip is to discuss the climate crisis regularly, to talk with children about their climate fears and not put it off,

47
00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:27.000
not delay talking about it until later.

48
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:34.000
Caroline also advises parents not to push it away, to choose to forget about or ignore the subject.

49
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:43.000
A better response is to tell kids honestly, we don't have all the answers, but by sharing ideas, we can work things out together.

50
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:48.000
A more hopeful message, and one that shared by climate champion Greta Turnberg.

51
00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:55.000
Yes, and it's time to reveal the answer to my question, how did Greta Turnberg's climate activism begin?

52
00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:00.000
I said it was by skipping school on Fridays, which was the correct answer.

53
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Greta started her school strike for climate in August 2018, before it was taken up by over 1.6 million school children

54
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:14.000
from 125 countries around the world.

55
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned from this program, starting with climate anxiety,

56
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:25.000
feeling worried, afraid, or depressed because of climate change.

57
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:29.000
A parasite is an animal or plant that feeds off another living thing.

58
00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:35.000
If something makes you feel very emotional or upset, you might say it freaks me out.

59
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:41.000
The idiom 1 and a million describes something which is extremely special, rare or unlikely.

60
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:50.000
And finally, two phrasal verbs to finish with, to put something off, which means to delay doing it to later and to push something away,

61
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
which means to decide to forget about or ignore it.

62
00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:02.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, but remember to join us again soon for more trending topics and useful vocabulary.

63
00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Here at six minutes English, goodbye for now.

64
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Goodbye.

65
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
6-nure English from BBCLearningEnglish.com
